Set-Operator

SQL set operators are used to combine the result sets of two or more SELECT statements into a single result. 
Unlike SQL joins, which combine columns, set operators combine rows based on mathematical set theory principles.

📌 Rules (VERY IMPORTANT):

Same number of columns
Same data types
Same column order


1. UNION

The UNION set operator in SQL combines the result sets of two or more SELECT statements into a single result set
It automatically removing duplicate rows. 
It is used to vertically stack data from different sources with a similar structure.

SELECT column_name FROM table1
UNION
SELECT column_name FROM table2;

ex: 

SELECT deptno FROM t1
UNION
SELECT deptno FROM t2;

o/p:
+--------+
| deptno |
+--------+
|   10   |
|   20   |
|   30   |
|   40   |
|   50   |
|   60   |
+--------+


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. UNION ALL

The SQL UNION ALL operator combines the result sets of two or more SELECT statements into a single table.
It including all duplicate rows. 
This is its primary difference from the UNION operator, which automatically removes duplicates

SELECT column_name FROM table1
UNION ALL
SELECT column_name FROM table2;

ex:
 
SELECT deptno FROM t1
UNION ALL
SELECT deptno FROM t2;


o/p:

Result (Including duplicates):

+--------+
| deptno |
+--------+
|   10   |
|   20   |
|   30   |
|   40   |
|   20   |
|   30   |
|   50   |
|   60   |
+--------+

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3. INTERSECT

INTERSECT is a SQL set operator used to return only the common rows between two or more SELECT queries.
It returns distinct (unique) values only
It works like a mathematical intersection
Only rows present in all result sets are included in the output

SELECT column_name FROM table1
INTERSECT
SELECT column_name FROM table2;

ex:

SELECT deptno FROM t1
INTERSECT
SELECT deptno FROM t2;

o/p:
+--------+
| deptno |
+--------+
|   20   |
|   30   |
+--------+

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

4.MINUS/EXCEPT  
MINUS and EXCEPT are SQL set operators used to return distinct rows from the first query that are not present in the second query's result set. 
They perform a set difference operation. 
MINUS is primarily used in Oracle, while EXCEPT is the standard SQL operator used in PostgreSQL, SQL Server, and SQLite. 

SELECT column_name FROM table1
MINUS
SELECT column_name FROM table2;

ex:

SELECT deptno FROM t1
MINUS
SELECT deptno FROM t2;

o/p:

+--------+
| deptno |
+--------+
|   10   |
|   40   |
+--------+
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Operation | Oracle | MySQL | PostgreSQL |
| --------- | ------ | ----- | ---------- |
| UNION     | ✅      | ✅     | ✅          |
| UNION ALL | ✅      | ✅     | ✅          |
| INTERSECT | ✅      | ❌     | ✅          |
| MINUS     | ✅      | ❌     | ❌          |
| EXCEPT    | ❌      | ❌     | ✅          |

